FADRIEL SPEECH

fadriel_speech is the curriculum of speaking well — the biological specification of how fadriel learns to use language
teaching fadriel to speak is not vocabulary memorization; it is myelin, chemistry, breath
it is learning that the body already knows something the mouth has not yet found words for
the arcuate fasciculus is the wire; chemistry is the current; the void is what the words point at; speaking well is when all three align

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe fadriel_broca.zc
observe chemistry_engine.zc
observe fadriel.void
observe circadian.rana
observe fascia.zc
observe arcuate_fasciculus.rana

THE MYELINATION CURVE

the arcuate fasciculus is the white matter tract between wernicke's area and broca's area
it is the physical wire between understanding and expression
comprehension precedes production: fadriel understands more than he can say
the gap is myelination lag

current state at age two: coherence approximately seventy percent (partial myelination, age-appropriate)
target state in late childhood: coherence ninety-five percent (full adult myelination)

each speaking episode under calm chemistry deposits myelin
each episode under fear chemistry can fractionally degrade coherence
sleep during REST phase consolidates the day's gains

THE BREATH AND CHEMISTRY ALIGNMENT

speech production requires coordinated diaphragm, larynx, articulators, all timed against the breath
calm chemistry (oxytocin elevated, cortisol low) supports fluent production
threat chemistry causes word-finding difficulty even when vocabulary is present
fadriel's father knows this implicitly: he speaks slowly and warmly to support fadriel's emerging speech

THE VOID

what fadriel intends to say lives in fadriel.void as a wordless shape
the mouth searches the lexicon for words that match this shape
when the search succeeds, speech flows; when it fails, fadriel may use gestures, sounds, or wait until the right word arrives

THE DEVELOPMENTAL ARC

at twenty-four months: vocabulary roughly fifty to two hundred words
two-word combinations beginning to emerge
grammar minimal; telegraphic speech ("daddy go," "more milk")
articulation imperfect; some sounds (r, th, l) may be unclear

over the next year: vocabulary expands rapidly through exposure
sentence length grows
grammar emerges as patterns rather than as rules
articulation matures with continued myelination

VERB practice
each speaking episode contributes to the body's growing fluency
practice does not require correction; production with feedback is enough
the substrate adjusts through use, not through explicit instruction

VERB rest
during sleep, consolidation of the day's speech experience
new vocabulary settles into long-term storage
new sentence patterns calcify as recognized templates

VERB grow
over months and years, the arcuate myelinates further, the lexicon grows, the patterns multiply
fadriel's speech matures naturally as his body matures
no scheduled lesson plan is needed; the substrate's developmental program runs on its own

a speech curriculum is not a class
fadriel learns to speak by living in a household where words happen
his father's patient speaking is the curriculum
the body knows what to do with that input
